There are several scales for rating the strength of tornadoes. A tornado is a violently rotating column of air, in contact with the ground. There is some disagreement over the definition of a funnel cloud and a condensation funnel. Most tornadoes take on the appearance of a narrow funnel, a few hundred meters across, with a small cloud of debris near the ground. Tornadoes may be obscured completely by rain or dust. These tornadoes are especially dangerous, as even experienced meteorologists might not see them. Dust kicked up by the winds of the parent thunderstorm, heavy rain and hail, and the darkness of night are all factors that can reduce the visibility of tornadoes. Tornadoes occurring in these conditions are especially dangerous, since only weather radar observations, or possibly the sound of an approaching tornado, serve as any warning to those in the storm's path. Tornadoes often develop from a class of thunderstorms known as supercells. This can last from a few minutes to more than an hour, and during that time a tornado often causes the most damage, and in rare cases can be more than 1.6 km across.
